05148nam a22007215i 9780231527019DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2010033894  a(OCoLC)979574504  a97802315270197 a10.7312/lobe153142doi  a(DE-B1597)459070  a(OCoLC)796813112  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBL51b.L5755 2011 4aBL51b.L5755 2015 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a202.112231 aLobel, Diana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Quest for God and the Good :bWorld Philosophy as a Living Experience /cDiana Lobel. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. “God Saw That It Was Good”: The Creation of the World in the Hebrew Bible -- t2. A Divine Craftsman Shapes All for the Good: Plato’s Realm of the Forms -- t3. Change and the Good: Chinese Perspectives -- t4. The Harmony of Reason and Revelation: Augustine and Maimonides on Good and Evil -- t5. You Are the Absolute: Philosophies of India -- t6. Compassion, Wisdom, Awakening: The Way of Buddhism -- t7. The Good Is That to Which All Things Aim: Aristotle on God and the Good -- t8. The Philosopher as Teacher: Al- Fārābī on Contemplation and Action -- t9. The Imitation of God: Maimonides on the Active and the Contemplative Life -- t10. The Dance of Human Expression: Al-Ghazālī and Maimonides -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDiana Lobel takes readers on a journey across Eastern and Western philosophical and religious traditions to discover a beauty and purpose at the heart of reality that makes life worth living. Guided by the ideas of ancient thinkers and the insight of the philosophical historian Pierre Hadot, The Quest for God and the Good treats philosophy not as an abstract, theoretical discipline, but as a living experience. For centuries, human beings have struggled to know why we are here, whether a higher being or dimension exists, and whether our existence is fundamentally good. Above all, we want to know whether the search for God and the good will bring happiness. Following in the path of the ancient philosophers, Lobel directly connects conceptions of God or an Absolute with notions of the good, illuminating diverse classical texts and thinkers. She explores the Bible and the work of Plato, Aristotle, Augustine, Maimonides, al-Farabi, and al-Ghazali. She reads the Tao Te Ching, I Ching, Bhagavad Gita, and Upanishads, as well as the texts of Theravada, Mahayana, and Zen Buddhism, and traces the repercussions of these works in the modern thought of Alfred North Whitehead, Iris Murdoch, Alasdair MacIntyre, and Charles Taylor. While each of these texts and thinkers sets forth a distinct and unique vision, all maintain that human beings find fulfillment in their contact with beauty and purpose. Rather than arriving at one universal definition of God or the good, Lobel demonstrates the aesthetic value of multiple visions presented by many thinkers across cultures. The Quest for God and the Good sets forth a path of investigation and discovery culminating in intellectual and spiritual communion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aGodvComparative studies. 0aGood and evilxReligious aspectsvComparative studies. 0aPhilosophy and religion. 0aReligious lifevComparative studies. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/lobe1531440uhttps://www.d